Step 1: Create Web Servers (Backend)

Install Apache (or Nginx) on both backend VMs:

sudo apt update
sudo apt install -y apache2
Identify each server (IMPORTANT)

On Web1:

echo "This is Web Server 1" | sudo tee /var/www/html/index.html

On Web2:

echo "This is Web Server 2" | sudo tee /var/www/html/index.html
Add Health Check Endpoint
echo "OK" | sudo tee /var/www/html/health

Test:

http://192.168.56.11/health
http://192.168.56.12/health
⚙️ Step 2: Setup HAProxy VM

Install HAProxy:

sudo apt update
sudo apt install -y haproxy
⚙️ Step 3: Configure HAProxy

Edit config:

sudo nano /etc/haproxy/haproxy.cfg
Full Working Config (Enhanced)
global
    log /dev/log local0
    maxconn 4096
    daemon

defaults
    log global
    mode http
    option httplog
    timeout connect 5s
    timeout client 50s
    timeout server 50s

frontend http_in
    bind *:80
    mode http

    # ACL Example (Block specific IP)
    acl blocked_ip src 192.168.56.1
    http-request deny if blocked_ip

    default_backend web_pool

backend web_pool
    mode http
    balance roundrobin

    # Health check
    option httpchk GET /health

    # Sticky session (cookie-based)
    cookie SERVERID insert indirect nocache

    server web1 192.168.56.11:80 check cookie w1
    server web2 192.168.56.12:80 check cookie w2
 Step 4: SSL Termination
Create Self-Signed Certificate
sudo mkdir -p /etc/ssl/haproxy

sudo openssl req -x509 -nodes -days 365 \
-newkey rsa:2048 \
-keyout /etc/ssl/haproxy/cert.pem \
-out /etc/ssl/haproxy/cert.pem
Update frontend
frontend https_in
    bind *:443 ssl crt /etc/ssl/haproxy/cert.pem
    mode http
    default_backend web_pool
 Step 5: Restart HAProxy
sudo systemctl restart haproxy
